ons are and what 'rational' use of information actually means. The examples used include controversies about nature-nurture, climate change, gender roles, vaccination, genetically modified food and artificial intelligence. Drawing on cutting-edge scholarship as well as personal experiences of culture clashes, the book is aimed at the general, educated public as well as students and scholars interested in the interface of human motivation and the urgent social problems of today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBelief and doubt. 0aFake newsxSocial aspects. 0aInsight. 0aKnowledge, Sociology of. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Knowledge Capital.2bisacsh  aFact resistance.  aIgnorance studies.  aKnowledge resistance.  aclimate change.  adenial.  aepistemic uncertainty.  afact resistance.  afake news.  aignorance studies.  aknowledge resistance.  aknowledge tribes.  astrategic ignorance.  avaccination.1 aKlintman, Mikael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615870340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526158703423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526158703/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles